{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_017hsFN4uPEqpz1txyggP3GD","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me analyze each behavior carefully using the framework provided.\n\n**Behavior 1**: Storing a PASS review summary is blocked when any stored dimension finding for the same round has a FAIL verdict.\n\n- MOCK-MISS: This is about validation logic when storing a summary. Could be a single function that checks stored findings before allowing a PASS summary to be stored. If it's checking stored data (local DB/filesystem), this could be Integration (modules wiring together). But if it's purely a validation function that takes findings as input and returns blocked/allowed, it could be Unit.\n- REAL-INFRA: No OS/network needed. The \"stored findings\" could be a local DB or in-memory store. \n\nAn in-process fake can reproduce this behavior since the core logic is validating against stored findings—the real question is whether we're testing the validation function in isolation or how it integrates with the storage layer. If we mock storage, we might hide failures in how the system actually queries and checks those findings, so an integration test that wires both modules together would be more likely to catch the real failure mode where the storage layer returns the findings correctly but the validation logic doesn't check them properly.\n\nFor the stop-gate verdict computation, the key issue is whether it's actually reading from stored findings or just relying on summary text. Mocking storage could let us verify the gate reads from storage, but we need to confirm it's reading the actual findings and not just the hand-written summary. This also requires integration testing to wire the storage with the gate logic and verify the behavior.\n\nFor manual summary overrides, there are two requirements: an explicit override flag must be present, and a warning record must be produced. Since the warning record likely involves storage interaction, integration testing is the right level to verify both the flag requirement and the warning record creation.\n\nNow looking at Behavior 4 regarding the gate requirements after Phase 4 fixes...\n\nThe gate needs to verify that a review round identifier exists with a timestamp after the latest fix commit. The tricky part is whether this requires real git operations—if I'm reading actual commit history from git, that pushes it to system level. But if both the commit timestamp and review round identifier can be mocked in storage, then integration testing works. The core question is whether the temporal ordering between git commits and review rounds can be faked or needs real git data.\n\nFor behavior 5, the gate is checking that PASS can't finalize without a fresh review-agent round running on the updated diff. This involves an agent making actual decisions, which suggests agentic-level testing if the agent uses an LLM. The \"updated diff\" might require real diff computation, but the main constraint is whether the review-agent round actually executes and produces a result. the actual review agent needs to run on the updated diff, not just that the gate checks for a round identifier—so this is really about testing the agentic behavior in the live workflow, which makes it Agentic rather than just Integration. on the updated diff\" part is important. Does it actually need to verify the agent ran on the correct diff? That requires Agentic or Workflow.\n\nI'll go with Workflow since it's about the live multi-step review process.\n\nActually, re-reading: \"In the live review loop, PASS cannot finalize unless a fresh review-agent round runs on the updated diff.\" This is specifically about the enforcement in the live loop. The failure mode is: can PASS finalize without the agent having run on the updated diff? \n\nIf the test just checks that the gate enforces a post-fix round identifier exists, that's Integration. But \"live review loop\" and \"fresh review-agent round runs on the updated diff\" suggests we need to actually run the loop.\n\nI'll say minimum is Workflow given \"live review loop\" language, but Integration is plausible if we interpret it as just gate enforcement.\n\nFor Behavior 6, I'm looking at what happens when review rounds run out with unresolved MUST-FIX findings still in the stored results. This is really about the storage layer plus the gate logic that checks those results. I don't need the LLM or real infrastructure, and it's not multi-step orchestration. I can mock the storage, populate it with MUST-FIX findings, exhaust the rounds, and verify the gate produces escalation instead of PASS. That's Integration level.\n\nNow for Behavior 7, it's similar but explicitly in a live multi-round workflow context—exhausted rounds with unresolved MUST-FIX findings still block PASS and trigger escalation. Behavior 6 is about a deterministic gate check—when review rounds are exhausted with unresolved MUST-FIX findings in storage, the system escalates rather than passing. This is pure Integration logic since it reads stored data and makes a decision without needing an LLM. Behavior 7 is the broader Workflow pattern of the live multi-round review loop itself triggering escalation when exhausted. Both are correctly classified.\n\nFor behavior 4, I need to think through the temporal ordering requirement more carefully—the gate needs to verify that a review round identifier was produced after the latest fix commit, which means it's checking commit history against review metadata. This crosses the boundary into Integration since it's wiring together commit state and review state.\n\nNow I'm assigning confidence levels to each behavior. Behavior 1 is most likely Integration since it involves the storage layer blocking PASS summaries based on dimension findings. Behavior 2 is strongly Integration—the gate and storage need to be wired together to enforce the rule. Behavior 3 requires the warning record to actually persist, so Integration with storage is the right level. Behavior 4 also lands on Integration because it's coordinating commit metadata with round metadata through the gate logic.\n\nBehavior 5 is different—this one's Workflow-heavy at 0.65 since it's orchestrating the entire flow of reading commits, applying gates, and recording outcomes. Behavior 6 is Integration again, coordinating the override mechanism with storage. Behavior 7 is still being evaluated.\n\nNow I'm working through the detailed justifications for each behavior. For behavior 1, the core issue is that the failure requires two modules to interact—the storage layer holding per-dimension findings and the validation layer checking those findings before accepting a PASS summary. A unit test alone wouldn't catch how the system retrieves findings from storage, so I need an integration test that sets up storage with a FAIL dimension finding and then attempts to store a PASS summary to verify the conflict is caught.\n\nFor behavior 2, the gate must actually read from storage rather than trusting the summary text itself, which only fails at the integration boundary. I'll populate storage with FAIL findings while the summary says \"all PASS\" and verify the gate computation returns FAIL based on what's stored, not what the text claims.\n\nFor behavior 3, I need to verify both that the override flag is checked and that the warning record actually persists in auditable storage—the audit trail only matters if it's real. I'm setting up a test where attempting to store a summary override without the flag should be rejected.\n\nFor behavior 4, the temporal ordering between commit timestamp and round identifier requires wiring multiple modules together, so I'll use an in-process fake that stores round IDs with timestamps. I'm testing that a PASS finalization gets blocked when a fix commit comes before the review round, then allowed after a new round is created with a later timestamp.\n\nFor behavior 5, \"in the live review loop\" and \"fresh review-agent round runs on the updated diff\" require the actual workflow to execute with a real review agent present.\n\nFor behavior 6, this is pure state machine logic—just reading stored MUST-FIX findings and checking the round counter—so I don't need the LLM to run again. I'm pre-populating storage with MUST-FIX findings across all allowed rounds, signaling rounds are exhausted, then verifying the outcome determination returns an escalation result.\n\nFor behavior 7, I need to actually run the full multi-round review workflow to exhaustion without resolving the MUST-FIX findings, then confirm the workflow emits an escalation signal instead of allowing PASS.\n\nAll of these should have plan_consistent set to true since my test descriptions align with the chosen test levels. For behavior 1, even though I'm using in-process fake storage, that's still appropriate for an Integration test.\n\nNow I'm reconsidering behavior 5—the question is whether testing \"PASS cannot finalize unless a fresh review-agent round runs\" requires a Workflow level test or if Integration would suffice. The behavior explicitly mentions \"live review loop\" and \"fresh review-agent round runs,\" which suggests I'm testing the actual loop execution rather than just the gate logic in isolation. That points to Workflow being the right level. me reconsider: \"PASS cannot finalize unless a fresh review-agent round runs on the updated diff\" - the failure mode is: can PASS finalize without the agent having run? Testing this at Integration would set up storage without a fresh round ID for the current diff, attempt to finalize PASS, and verify it's blocked. That would be Integration-level. The \"live review loop\" could just be context, not necessarily requiring the full live workflow.\n\nBehavior 5 focuses on a single constraint—the fresh round requirement—while behavior 7 explicitly covers the exhaustion scenario in a live workflow. I'll keep behavior 5 as Workflow (0.65 probability) but acknowledge Integration as plausible (0.15).\n\nActually, let me think through this more systematically. For the REJECTION-GATE check, could I demote from Workflow to Integration? The key question is whether \"fresh review-agent round RUNS\" means the agent actually needs to execute, or if I just need to verify the constraint is enforced by checking a stored identifier. If the gate only checks a stored round identifier, Integration testing suffices. If we need the agent to actually run to verify the constraint works end-to-end, then Workflow is required. The wording \"RUNS\" suggests actual execution, but from a testing perspective, I might only need to verify the enforcement mechanism itself.\n\nThe real failure mode is: can PASS finalize without a fresh round? An Integration test would fake the storage, verify the gate blocks PASS without a fresh round ID, and that would catch the failure. The live loop context might just be background information, not a requirement for the test level. I'll settle on Workflow for behavior 5 (0.65 probability) with a note that Integration is defensible (0.15).\n\nNow I'm finalizing my decisions across all seven behaviors: Integration, Integration, Integration, Integration, Workflow, Integration, Workflow.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":10556,"cache_read_input_tokens":3097,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":10556},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"0c83ea0d-2205-445d-bd9c-f54e02eb0aa0","uuid":"e940539e-2744-4c4e-b5b0-00c4579436c2"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_017hsFN4uPEqpz1txyggP3GD","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_018wyKx4ZHqPbFoc88Z5S8vp","name":"StructuredOutput","input":{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"Storing a PASS review summary is blocked when any stored dimension finding for the same round has a FAIL verdict.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure only manifests at the boundary between the summary-write path and the dimension-findings storage layer. A unit test that injects findings as arguments into a validation function cannot catch a bug where the summary writer queries the wrong round ID, queries the wrong table, or skips the check entirely. REAL-INFRA: No OS or real network required; an in-process fake store is sufficient. MOCK-HIDE: Mocking the findings store always returns whatever the test says, masking the real query logic. LLM-DEP: No model output involved. MULTI-STEP: No. The bug in the issue (summary composed without querying stored per-dimension results) is precisely a module-boundary failure — the summary writer and the findings store must be wired together to expose it. REJECTION-GATE: Demoting to Unit would require passing findings directly into the validation function, which skips the retrieval path where the actual historical bug lived.","test_description":"Wire an in-process fake findings store and the summary-write service together. Insert one FAIL dimension finding for round R1 alongside other PASS findings. Call the store-summary API/function with a PASS verdict for round R1. Assert the call is rejected (exception, error result, or no write). Then replace the FAIL finding with a PASS and confirm the PASS summary is now accepted. Do not mock the findings retrieval logic.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.2,"Integration":0.65,"System":0.07,"Agentic":0.04,"Workflow":0.04}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"Stop-gate verdict computation reads per-dimension stored findings directly and does not rely only on hand-written summary text.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: This behavior is explicitly about the data source the gate consults. The only way to verify the gate reads storage (and not the summary blob) is to wire both modules together and create a contradiction: FAIL in storage with PASS in summary text. A unit test that passes findings as arguments proves nothing about whether the production call site actually passes storage-derived data. REAL-INFRA: In-process fake store is sufficient; no OS or network needed. MOCK-HIDE: Mocking the store makes both code paths (reads storage vs. reads summary) pass identically. LLM-DEP: None. REJECTION-GATE: Cannot demote to Unit — the distinguishing failure only appears when the gate's actual retrieval call is exercised against a real (or fake-but-wired) store holding contradictory data.","test_description":"Seed an in-process fake findings store with FAIL verdicts for dimensions D1 and D2 for round R1. Set the summary text field for R1 to 'all dimensions PASS'. Invoke the stop-gate verdict computation for R1. Assert the returned verdict is FAIL (not PASS). Verify no code path reads from the summary text field by temporarily stubbing that field to an empty or absent value and confirming the result is unchanged.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.12,"Integration":0.75,"System":0.06,"Agentic":0.04,"Workflow":0.03}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"Manual summary text overrides require an explicit override flag and produce an auditable warning record.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: Two sub-behaviors must both hold: (a) flag enforcement (could be unit) and (b) the warning record actually persists in auditable storage. Sub-behavior (b) only fails at the boundary between the override handler and the audit-log storage. REAL-INFRA: In-process fake audit store is sufficient. MOCK-HIDE: Mocking audit storage always succeeds, hiding a missing write. LLM-DEP: None. MULTI-STEP: None. REJECTION-GATE: Cannot demote to Unit because the audit trail is meaningful only if it is actually written to the storage layer, not just returned as a return value from a pure function.","test_description":"Attempt to store a manual summary override without the override flag set — assert the call is rejected. Then repeat with the override flag set. Assert the call succeeds AND query the audit log store to confirm a warning record exists with: the round ID, the override actor, a timestamp, and the overridden summary text. Confirm the warning record is retrievable independently of the summary record (i.e., deletion of summary does not remove the audit entry).","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.18,"Integration":0.65,"System":0.1,"Agentic":0.04,"Workflow":0.03}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"After Phase 4 fixes, the gate requires a review round identifier produced after the latest fix commit before PASS can be finalized.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure involves temporal ordering across two storage entities: (1) fix-commit metadata and (2) review-round identifiers. The gate must query both and compare timestamps. This is a multi-module boundary failure. REAL-INFRA: Commit timestamps can be represented as stored metadata in an in-process fake; real git subprocess is not required because the gate consumes an abstracted commit reference, not raw git output. If real git is required, demote to System, but the behavior text ('round identifier produced after the latest fix commit') suggests an abstracted record, not a raw git call. MOCK-HIDE: Mocking either storage module makes the ordering check trivially pass. LLM-DEP: None. REJECTION-GATE: Cannot demote to Unit because the comparison requires querying two separate storage records.","test_description":"In an in-process fake store: (1) record fix-commit C1 at timestamp T=100. (2) Store a review round R_old with timestamp T=80 (before the fix). (3) Attempt PASS finalization referencing R_old — assert blocked. (4) Store a new review round R_new with timestamp T=120 (after the fix). (5) Attempt PASS finalization referencing R_new — assert allowed. Additionally, verify that if no fix-commit is recorded (Phase 4 not yet reached), the temporal check is skipped or treated as always-satisfied per spec.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.08,"Integration":0.55,"System":0.27,"Agentic":0.05,"Workflow":0.05}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"In the live review loop, PASS cannot finalize unless a fresh review-agent round runs on the updated diff.","minimum_level":"Workflow","justification":"MOCK-MISS: 'In the live review loop' scopes the behavior to the actual executing pipeline, not just the gate predicate in isolation. REAL-INFRA: The 'updated diff' and 'review-agent round' are live artifacts produced by real pipeline steps. LLM-DEP: A 'review-agent round' involves a real AI review agent making judgments on the diff; a stub that always returns canned findings cannot verify that the enforcement actually prevents PASS before a real agent runs on the correct diff version. MULTI-STEP: The failure scenario is inherently sequential: apply fix → (incorrectly) skip agent re-run → attempt to finalize PASS. Verifying the block requires the pipeline to progress through these steps. REJECTION-GATE: Cannot demote to Integration — the Integration-level test would only verify the gate's stored-round-ID predicate, but would not catch a live-loop code path that bypasses the gate or uses a stale diff reference. Cannot demote to Agentic alone because the relevant failure spans the sequence: fix application → agent dispatch → gate check.","test_description":"Run the full PR review pipeline against a real (or sandbox) diff that has a MUST-FIX finding. Apply a patch to the diff. Attempt to finalize PASS without dispatching a new review-agent round on the patched diff — assert the pipeline blocks finalization. Then trigger a fresh review-agent round on the patched diff, wait for it to complete, and reattempt finalization — assert it succeeds (assuming no new MUST-FIX findings). Confirm via audit log that the round identifier used for finalization was created after the patch timestamp.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.14,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.15,"Workflow":0.65}},{"behavior_id":6,"description":"If review rounds are exhausted with unresolved MUST-FIX findings in stored results, the outcome is escalation rather than PASS.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: Two modules must be wired: (1) the round-counter/exhaustion tracker and (2) the findings store containing MUST-FIX verdicts. The gate's outcome logic consults both. A unit test could inject both as arguments, but the real bug scenario (rounds exhausted, findings still say MUST-FIX, gate returns PASS anyway) only manifests when the gate actually queries the persistent state of both. REAL-INFRA: In-process fake store is sufficient; no real subprocess or network needed. MOCK-HIDE: Mocking either dependency causes the test to pass regardless of the gate's actual query logic. LLM-DEP: The LLM already ran and its outputs are the stored findings; the gate decision here is purely deterministic over stored data. MULTI-STEP: None — this is a single gate invocation over pre-populated state. REJECTION-GATE: Cannot escalate to Agentic because the LLM's output is already frozen in storage; correctness does not depend on what a real model produces at test time.","test_description":"Using an in-process fake store, set the round counter to max (all rounds exhausted) and populate dimension findings for the current round with at least one MUST-FIX verdict unresolved. Invoke the outcome-determination function. Assert the return value is ESCALATION (not PASS, not FAIL-and-retry). Confirm no PASS summary record is written to the findings store. As a contrast case, set all findings to PASS with rounds exhausted and verify the outcome is PASS (not escalation), to ensure the escalation path is conditioned on unresolved findings.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.22,"Integration":0.66,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.04,"Workflow":0.03}},{"behavior_id":7,"description":"In a live multi-round review workflow, exhausted rounds with unresolved MUST-FIX findings still block PASS and emit escalation.","minimum_level":"Workflow","justification":"MOCK-MISS: 'Live multi-round review workflow' explicitly places this behavior in the executing pipeline, not in isolated gate logic. REAL-INFRA: The workflow involves real diff processing and real agent invocations across multiple rounds. LLM-DEP: Each review round uses a real AI review agent; a stub that always returns canned MUST-FIX findings cannot verify that the live workflow's escalation path fires correctly when agents produce those verdicts through real execution (e.g., the workflow might have a code path that short-circuits escalation when it detects stubbed calls). MULTI-STEP: Explicitly multi-round — 'exhausted rounds' requires simulating N sequential review-agent rounds all returning unresolved MUST-FIX, then verifying the workflow transitions to escalation rather than looping or emitting PASS. REJECTION-GATE: Behavior 6 covers the Integration-level predicate; this behavior explicitly adds 'live' and 'multi-round' context, which disqualifies Integration. Cannot stay at Agentic (single model call) because multiple sequential agent rounds must each run and each produce findings before the exhaustion condition is met.","test_description":"Run the full PR review pipeline with a max-rounds limit of N (e.g., 3). For each round, the real review agent evaluates the diff and returns at least one MUST-FIX finding (use a diff that reliably produces findings, or a sandboxed deterministic agent). After N rounds complete without any finding being resolved, assert: (1) the pipeline does not emit PASS, (2) an escalation event is emitted (e.g., webhook, message, or flag), (3) the escalation event references the unresolved MUST-FIX finding IDs, and (4) no further review rounds are dispatched.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.05,"System":0.04,"Agentic":0.1,"Workflow":0.8}}]},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":10556,"cache_read_input_tokens":3097,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":10556},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"0c83ea0d-2205-445d-bd9c-f54e02eb0aa0","uuid":"5cb2a55e-493b-4351-a3d7-cc0f099fcffe"}
